    conclusion: "Whilst this paper has primarily focused on the negative ramifications that follow, when governments excessively rely on consultancy services for their assessments and recommendations to effect key policy formulations, it in no way suggests the total alienation of consultancy firms by governments, for in a world where economies are advancing at a rapid pace, with newer technologies coming to the fore, wherein governmental know-how would be understandably limited, therefore requiring the services of consultancy firms , which are adept at handling such novel applications where the public sector has limited expertise. The problem arises when the lines between policy making by the state and the same by consultancy firms gets hazy, raising questions of locus standi of such firms to decide to key policy matters, over democratically elected governments , with the people’s mandate. The more prudent approach rather is the need to regulate the relationship between governments and consultancy firms, wherein the elaborately deliberated issue of conflict of interest would be taken care of, with due diligence, making sure that one who assists in policy making does not end up benefitting the very subject the policy seeks to control. The public sector and more importantly civil servants play a vital role in this entire process, investing in knowledge accumulation would make for great strides, for it would instill a necessary tinge of self-sufficiency with governmental oversight in sensitive sectors where the risk of an exposure is always lurking, with many things hanging in balance. The initial hypothesis of huge ramifications holds true, aptly proven by various instances deliberated upon, in this study, be it McKinsey and Co.’s aggressive marketing pitch (of OxyContin) despite the worsening opioid addiction crisis, or the case of Disney, where cost-cutting in maintenance lead to many accidents, all of these incidents point to the lack of a ground-zero understanding of the matters at hand, with consultants detached from state of affairs being tasked with recommending policy changes. The key therefore, in the light of all of these considerations is to keep in mind, firmly, the fact that policy formulation is for governments to do, to aide them and provide key insights into areas in which the public sector has no experience is the limited task of consultancy firms, which is highly questionable the current scenario, with firms donning the hat of governments. Regulatory framework would ensure that there is more transparency regarding the functioning of consultancy firms whilst also ensuring their accountability.",
